			    STPJS 254</div>
  <p class="cont">build the Temple<span class="footRef">1</span> and the Nauvoo House;<span class="footRef">2</span> and that command is as binding upon us as any other;
  and that man who engages not in these things is as much a transgressor as though he broke any other
  commandment; he is not a doer of God&rsquo;s will,<span class="footRef">3</span> not a fulfiller of His laws.<span class="footRef">4</span></p>
  <div class="topic">The Saints Subject to Divine Counsel</div>
  <p class="std">In regard to the building up of Zion,<span class="footRef">5</span> it has to be done by the counsel of Jehovah, by the
  revelations of heaven; and we should feel to say, &ldquo;If the Lord go not with us, carry us not up
  hence.&rdquo;<span class="footRef">6</span> We would say to the Saints that come here, we have laid the foundation for the gathering
  of God&rsquo;s people<span class="footRef">7</span> to this place, and they expect that when the Saints do come, they will be under the
  counsel that God has appointed.<span class="footRef">8</span> The Twelve are set apart to counsel the Saints pertaining to this
  matter; and we expect that those who come here will send before them their wise men<span class="footRef">9</span> according
  to revelation; or if not practicable, be subject to the counsel that God has given,<span class="footRef">10</span> or they cannot
  receive an inheritance<span class="footRef">11</span> among the Saints, or be considered as God&rsquo;s people,<span class="footRef">12</span> and they will be dealt
  with as transgressors<span class="footRef">13</span> of the laws of God.<span class="footRef">14</span> We are trying here to gird up our loins,<span class="footRef">15</span> and purge from
  our midst the workers of iniquity;<span class="footRef">16</span> and we hope that when our brethren arrive from abroad, they will
  assist us to roll forth this good work,<span class="footRef">17</span> and to accomplish this great design that &ldquo;Zion may be built
  up in righteousness;<span class="footRef">18</span> and all nations flock to her standard;&rdquo;<span class="footRef">19</span> that as God&rsquo;s people, under His
  direction, and obedient to His law,<span class="footRef">20</span> we may grow up in righteousness and truth;<span class="footRef">21</span> that when His
  purposes shall be accomplished,<span class="footRef">22</span> we may receive an inheritance among those that are sanctified.<span class="footRef">23</span>
  (July 15, 1842.) DHC 5:61–66.</p>
  <div class="topic">Letter of the Prophet to Governor Carlin &mdash;</div>
  <div class="topic">Satisfied with the Governor&rsquo;s Attitude</div>
  <p class="std">Esteemed Sir:&mdash;Your favor of the 27th instant per Brevet Major-General Wilson Law is before
  me. I cannot let this opportunity pass without tendering to you my warmest thanks for the friendly
  treatment my lady as well as those with her received at your hands during the late visit, and also for
  the friendly feelings breathed forth in your letter. Your Excellency</p>
